one_reviews_text:
Overall I love the system. It really immerses you in games and is a lot of fun. I especially love it with driving games. Add a wheel, pedals and shifter to totally immerse yourself. There's just something about being able to look around inside a vehicle and at where you're going. Even though the graphics are still somewhat grainy in some situations my eyes adjust after a few minutes and that seems to melt away to a certain extent.However, keep in mind that VR in itself is still in it's early stages. A lot of the games that are currently out can tend to feel almost like demos as they are somewhat short. It's still a bit early in games being developed in VR and it's an expensive process so shorter games then you are used to can cost somewhat more. Some games can cause motion sickness in some people, if you are prone to this then you may want to reconsider. If you are expecting absolutely crisp graphics and can't accept certain things to be somewhat grainy then you may want to wait until VR in general advances. There are still bugs to be worked out and even though the dev team seems to be engaged with the community and are doing what they can to fix things, certain things can cause a bit of frustration trying to work out.A few accessories you may want to consider if you plan on purchasing a Rift:1. 10' HDMI extension cable (I bought 
C&E High Speed HDMI Extension Cable Male to Female, 10 Feet Supports Ethernet, 3D and Audio Return, CNE570921
). Although the Rift comes with about an 8' cord I needed more for my 15' X 15' space.2. 10' USB 3.0 extension cable (I bought 
Cable Matters SuperSpeed USB 3.0 Type A Male to Female Extension Cable in Black 10 Feet
). The headset plugs in with both HDMI and USB 3.03. A USB 3.0 PCIe card. Rift recommends 
Inateck Superspeed 4 Ports PCI-E to USB 3.0 Expansion Card - Interface USB 3.0 4-Port Express Card Desktop with 15 Pin SATA Power Connector, [ Include with A 4pin to 2x15pin Cable + A 15pin to 2x 15pin SATA Y-Cable 
] because this is one they know for sure works with the Rift. The sensors in the Rift are really power hungry. Sometimes, not in everyone's situation, the power draw of the sensors combined with whatever peripherals you have plugged in can draw too much power for your motherboard's USB controller. Also some USB 3.0 controllers don't play well with Rift. My USB 3.0 controller didn't play well with Rift so I purchased one and it works nicely.Even with the stated problems I do recommend the Rift if you want to feel more immersed in your gaming. It's a fun system and I don't regret my purchase at all. If you're not willing to work with some bumps and bugs though I'm not sure I would recommend it. You may want to wait for the next generation of VR if you're not willing to work with some drawbacks. Definitely make sure you run the Rift compatibility test  to make sure your PC is able to run it. One last thing to consider is if you wear prescription eye glasses as well. I had to buy some prescription lens inserts for mine because the headset smashed my glasses into my face making it uncomfortable. Not everyone who wears glasses seems to mind but I didn't like it.

Mind blown! I got this mainly for Elite Dangerous and it turned an already amazing game into an utterly stunning, immersive experience.
